    "doi": "10.1037/0278-7393.34.1.97",
    "mechanism": "A single computational system operates over item recognition states and priming activation. Each study trial encodes an item's features into memory. At test, a query activates partial features; activation spreads through associative links in the feature space, generating two concurrent processes: (1) accumulation of evidence for familiarity by summing feature overlap between query and memory trace, (2) speed-up of perceptual identification by residual activation from prior exposure. Priming manifests as faster identification independent of recognition; recognition requires threshold-crossing familiarity evidence. The model accounts for dissociations: items can prime (activate residual features) without recognition (insufficient threshold evidence) or elicit fluency differences (recognition affecting response criteria) without explicit source memory. No separate procedural or declarative systems are required.",
