    "doi": "10.1037/0278-7393.34.1.65",
    "mechanism": "A feature-based semantic space represents item meanings as vectors in a high-dimensional space. Semantic neighborhood is quantified as the density of nearby vectors (L2 or similar distance) and partitioned into near (close) and distant (far) neighbors. During identification, a neural activation dynamics evolves the input signal in competition with semantic neighbors. Stable states (attractors) in this dynamical system correspond to target and competitor semantic concepts. Near neighbors create strong competition (stronger attractors), slowing convergence; distant neighbors reduce competition pressure, accelerating convergence to the target. The model exhibits stable limit cycles and bifurcations as neighborhood density varies, producing opposite effects of proximity without ad-hoc inhibitory or facilitative mechanisms.",
